Reaching private instances.

The historical way to get a shell on a private instance was a bastion host, a hardened instance in a public subnet with secure-shell access locked down to your office address, used as a jump box into the private network. It still works, and agent forwarding keeps your private key off the bastion itself.

The modern answer is to skip the bastion entirely. Session manager, part of systems manager, opens a shell to any instance running its agent, with no open secure-shell port, no public subnet, no key pair, and every session audited and optionally recorded. Instance connect is similar for secure-shell-style access, pushing a one-time key through the ay-pee-eye.

Both work because the instance initiates the connection outward to AWS, so nothing inbound needs to be exposed; with a private endpoint, even that traffic stays off the internet. New infrastructure should default to session manager, with bastions as a fallback rather than the starting point.
